<br>
There were threads that openly and constructively discussed issues regarding class balance that were very helpful to everyone reading the thread. It made people think about alot of issues in ways they might not have thought of even if they didnt agree with it. The paladin class comes to mind (mainly because it was the most recent.) Thats what I would like to see here.<br>
<br>
Bottomline is this. No matter what you think of TLC, good or bad, I think that everyone can agree that it inadvertantly affects many people in ways that Verant could not foresee. So whats the alternative? <br>
<br>
I would really like to see some ideas from the other players out there. There were many that got posted on the test boards when this came up many months ago. Some were pretty good actually.<br>
<br>
Personally, what I would like to see is this. To prevent &quot;farming&quot; Verant should use the code they have developed in SoL that increase the level of the rare everytime it pops until it remains alive for &quot;x&quot; amount of time. Perhaps they can even increase the spawn time as well. So that if a rare is killed once, it would respawn at its normal spawn rate, but if it is killed again another 20 minutes would be added and so on, then they could out right remove TLC.<br>
<br>
If thats too much work, I would suggest Verant ask its content team to review all the quests above level 35 that require obtaining items from lower level NPC's. Once they have a list compiled of the drops on lower level mobs needed to complete these quests they can simply put these items on the loot tables of higher level mobs. That way they aren't penalizing the players that are higher level when new expansions come out.<br>
<br>
Perhaps they can do something similar with the components needed for trade skills. If human blood is needed for cultural armors I am sure they can add that item to a high level mob somewhere. How about FP guards? Those are light blue up till level 56.<br>
<br>
As an aside, its easy to just sit back and do nothing. Its easy to just say, &quot;Thats the way it is, so deal with it&quot;. If everyone in the world did that what a poorer people we would be. Change doesn't happen by itself. It starts with someone or some group saying, &quot;I have an idea&quot; or &quot;This could be better&quot;. In fact, as I recall, thats how EQ came to be in the first place isn't it?<br>
<br>
Lee Iacocca (fogive me is I mispelled this name) was one of the first to recongnize the power behind thinking differently and soliciting feedback from all levels of his organization. He recongnized that change doesn't have to be a bad thing. I'll leave you with one of his quotes, that is a personal favourite of mine.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lead, follow or get out of the way&quot;.<br>
<br>
Can't wait to hear your ideas.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
